                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d410">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">251.11 Insull, Samuel/228: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The <gloss type="from">Acting Secretary of State</gloss> to
                        the Minister in Greece (<persName type="to">MacVeagh</persName>)</hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Washington</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1933-11-22T15:00:00-05:00"
                            >November 22, 1933—3 p.m.</date>
                    </dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>58. Your 116, November 16, noon. In the event that the Greek Government decides
                    to expel Insull, and if it is necessary for him to be furnished with a valid
                    travel document in order that such expulsion may be effected, the Department
                    would be willing to rescind the cancellation of his passport accomplished by the
                    Department’s telegram of January 5, 1933, and to notify American Consular
                    officers accordingly. Insull could be notified that the Secretary of State had
                    authorized the cancellation to be rescinded.</p>
                <p>Please continue to keep the Department informed of developments. Please advise
                    Harness that the Department of Justice desires him to remain in Athens pending
                    further instructions.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Phillips</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
